      <div class="row featurette">
        <div class="col-md-12">
          <h2 id="WCC2013Game3" class="featurette-heading"> Magnus Carlsen vs Viswanathan Anand, Game 3.<span class="text-muted"> Magnus stumbles again as white, Anand too passive to seize control. </span></h2>
          <p>Thoughts about Magnus-Anand game 3.  </p>
          <p>Magnus is trying way too hard here.  He is, by far, the best chess player on this planet.  He should just play his game.  Start with 1. e4 and do the Ruy Lopez.  Sure, Anand will likely have some tricks, but you can't play the Reti opening every game the next 4 times you play white.  The first game Magnus tried this, he barely equalized and had to rely on Anand being content with a draw.  Then, third game he runs the Reti again!  You can see Magnus's state of mind when he plays 13. Bb4.  It's a forcing move and aggressive.  But surely he accounted for 13... Be6, which forces the Queen back with tempo.  All the major analytics engines agree that white had around a 0.3 advantage but after 13. Bb4, black now has a better position.  He has a centralized bishop now in the same position and removes one of white's bishops.  </p>
          <p>While it's possible and even likely he has some theoretical improvement on the main Reti lines, I feel he's thrown off by Anand's reputation as an excellent match player with openings.  It doesn't help that Anand has Peter Leko helping him as a second either.  </p>
          <p>I like how the 2013 chess championship is streamed and annotated by Susan Polgar and Ramesh.  Both are top-notch commentators and players.  But it would be helpful to split up the commentary into 2 different commentaries.  Have 1 commentator talk to actual players and 1 talk to people who know the basic moves.  Beginners are going to be bored and confused when commentators discuss transposing from one opening to another in detail, but amateurs are going to be bored if you talk about how your pawns shouldn't be doubled.    </p> 
          <p>As an amateur player, I'm rooting for Magnus here.  He's the type of swashbuckling marketable persona chess needs to have a breakthrough.  But the old chess captain me is telling me that Anand holds the advantage here.  He's making Magnus play his game.</p>  
    </div>
